# ── PREFERRED CITATION: companion paper ──────────────────────────────────
# Update doi, journal, volume, issue, start, and end when the paper is
# accepted. Until then, use type: unpublished and the preprint url.
preferred-citation:
  type: unpublished
  # ── When accepted, change type to "article" and fill in the fields below:
  # type: article
  # doi: "10.XXXXX/XXXXX"            # assign at acceptance
  # journal: "Artificial Intelligence and Law"   # confirm at acceptance
  # volume: X
  # issue: X
  # start: X
  # end: X

  title: >-
    Machine-checkable compliance for AGI Governance: Formalizing
    principles as auditable norms and evidence-linked indicators

  authors:
    - family-names: "Corona Fraga"
      given-names: "Pablo"
      orcid: "https://orcid.org/0000-0001-5012-9468"
      affiliation: >-
        INFOTEC — Research Center for Information and
        Communication Technologies, Mexico City, Mexico

    - family-names: "Diab"
      given-names: "Amin M.E-A."
      orcid: "https://orcid.org/0009-0008-4069-885X"
      affiliation: >-
        Johns Hopkins Whiting School of Engineering,
        Johns Hopkins University, Baltimore, MD, USA

    - family-names: "Hwang"
      given-names: "Sun Ho"
      orcid: "https://orcid.org/0009-0008-7161-2641"
      affiliation: >-
        Johns Hopkins Whiting School of Engineering Alumnus,
        Johns Hopkins University, Baltimore, MD, USA

    - family-names: "Diaz"
      given-names: "Vanessa"
      orcid: "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-7186-8785"
      affiliation: >-
        Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation, Mexico

  year: 2026
  month: 3

  abstract: >-
    This article proposes a machine-checkable governance compliance model
    for AGI that operationalizes widely recognized principles
    (transparency, accountability, beneficence/non-maleficence, fairness,
    human control, robustness and security, and industry-community
    collaboration) as formal norms and measurable indicators grounded in
    concrete evidence artifacts. Building on a systematic evidence
    mapping, normative triangulation with contemporary risk governance
    frameworks — including ISO/IEC 42001:2023 and the EU AI Act — and an
    indicator synthesis from comparative evaluations of foundation models,
    the paper defines a computable knowledge model linking principles,
    controls, indicators, and evidence; a formal specification of a
    compliance-checking procedure with reference architecture; and a
    pre-registered prospective evaluation framework for high-impact
    deployments.

  keywords:
    - artificial intelligence
    - artificial general intelligence
    - AI governance
    - legal compliance checking
    - normative reasoning
    - audit evidence
    - risk management
    - ISO/IEC 42001
    - AI management systems
    - deontic logic
    - LegalRuleML
